Add a per-skb timestamp field to struct sk_buff in
include/linux/skbuff.h, used to carry the start-of-delay timestamp
from the protocol-stack entry point through to the RX/TX accounting
end point.

Field choice: we cannot reuse skb->tstamp (already used by
SO_TIMESTAMPNS / packet scheduling) and skb->cb is owned by each
layer.  A dedicated __u64 delayacct_start is the cleanest option.

The field is #ifdef-protected so kernels without
CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT see no growth in struct sk_buff.

The complete unified diff (apply with `git apply` or `patch -p1`
from the root of a Linux 6.6 source tree):

--- a/include/linux/skbuff.h
+++ b/include/linux/skbuff.h
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ struct sk_buff {
 	/* receive queue (rarely used field) */
 	__u32			rxhash;

+#ifdef CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT
+	/* start time for net-delayacct, in ns; 0 = not stamped */
+	__u64			delayacct_start;
+#endif
 	/* private: */
 	__u32			headers_end[0];

Alternative placement (near skb->tstamp):

@@ -XXX,XXX @@ struct sk_buff {
 	ktime_t			tstamp;
+#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT)
+	__u64			delayacct_start;
+#endif
 	/* private: */

Note: the exact context lines may vary slightly between 6.6.x point
releases.  When applying, pick any cache-line-friendly spot inside
struct sk_buff; the field is accessed only in the net-delayacct
helpers, so its exact offset does not matter functionally.
